ğŸ§  Concepts Reviewed & Clarified
ğŸ§¨ Exploitation & Attacks

Buffer Overflow
A vulnerability that occurs when an application receives more data than a buffer can handle, causing excess data to overwrite adjacent memory locations (such as registers). This can allow attackers to alter execution flow and run arbitrary code on the target system.

ğŸ” PKI, Certificates & Encryption

PKI Certificates
Digital certificates used to verify the identity and authenticity of a server or entity. PKI certificates enable secure communication and are commonly used to secure web applications via HTTPS.

HTTPS
A secure version of HTTP that encrypts data transmitted over the internet using SSL/TLS, protecting against interception and tampering.

Certificate Validity Period
The time window during which a certificate is considered valid and trusted. Determined by the issuing Certificate Authority (CA), typically ranging from 1â€“3 years. Validity can be verified by checking the â€œvalid fromâ€ and â€œvalid toâ€ dates.

Domain Name in PKI Certificates
Specifies the website or web application the certificate is issued for. Can be:

A specific domain (e.g., app.comptia.org)

A wildcard domain (e.g., *.comptia.org)
Wildcard certificates secure multiple subdomains such as payment.comptia.org and contact.comptia.org.

ğŸ§ª Network Scanning & Enumeration

Nmap (Network Mapper)
A tool used to scan IP addresses and ports to discover hosts, open ports, services, and applications running on a system. Nmap helps administrators and security professionals:

Identify running services

Detect OS and service versions

Perform script scans

Conduct vulnerability scanning

Map firewall rules and exposure

ğŸ“‰ Practice Exam Takeaways

Mistakes today are mostly related to:

How exploits work internally

